Barack Obama will be the fourth American President to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
American President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo, Norway, to spend 26 hours and be the fourth American President of History to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
The $1.4 million diploma, medal and cheque will be given to him, among other things, for his outstanding efforts to strengthen global diplomacy and collaboration among nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will land in the morning in the Norwegian metropolis and have a busy program.
He will first visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time the five members of the Committee who chose him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The planning of the presidential couple then provides for an interview with the King of Norway Harald V and Queen Sonja.
The visit will have its summum in the afternoon at a solemn ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth American President to receive it, but only the third who will be awarded the award in the Committee's own forum.
The White House informed in advance that Obama would talk about the war in Afghanistan when the award was awarded.
The President does not want to avoid this subject because he is aware that he is receiving this award by being a President who is leading a war in two countries at this time.
He strengthened the war effort a few days ago by sending additional units to Afghanistan, which none of his critics will forget to underline.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a cheque of 10 million Swedish kroons (about 1.1 million Euros).
He intends to donate it to charitable works, but he has not yet made a concrete decision on which.
His programme will then take him and his wife to a banquet, including, in addition to the king and queen of Norway, the head of government and 250 other guests.
Obama was rather reluctant at this price at first.
He mentioned, for example, having the feeling not to deserve it fully.
He has also repeated several times that it is not a price for himself alone, but for all those who defend the same values as him.
From the time of the announcement, he said it would be an "invitation to act."
