Czech Discovery: a substance that works on "enduring" HIV viruses as well
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new combinations that can slow down the proliferation of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed drug immunity.
This reality takes, in some cases, the top of the fact that the combination does not act so intensely on the common variants of the virus as well as some medicines already available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at this time.
However, the lives of patients can be radically extended through a mixture of medicines that prevent the spread of HIV virus in the body.
Their consumption, however, results in a series of side effects.
In addition, the repression of this multiplication has the effect of developing what are called resistant viruses on which the drugs no longer have an effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Science of the Czech Republic, the VŠCHT of Prague and the University of Heidelberg, opens the way for a way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metalocarborans act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarborans are a combination of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all the drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The work of the researchers leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their links to the virus's proteins.
Metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multiple-wall cages are formed by boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A trash-resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
