Redigited in the country's constitution in 1978, China's single child policy is, without doubt, the most controversial obligation introduced by the Communist government.
Couples who violate this policy may have to pay colossal fines -- up to three times their annual income -- and suffer discrimination in the workplace.
The Chinese authorities have assigned the duty to the police to help the country avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while human rights lawyers have denounced abuses in the implementation of this policy.
In rural areas, some representatives of the authority have forced pregnant women from a second child to abort.
In addition, many couples have used selective abortions leading to an abnormally high ratio of boys to girls.
In recent years, the authorities responsible for the population have gradually softened their position on the single child policy.
In 2004, they granted more exceptions to the rule -- including for urban residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases in which men and women are already single children -- and in 2007 they softened a lot of their hard slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, Professor at the Institute of Population Research at the University of Beijing, said that the central government authorities have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the partners is a single child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage births.
In no time, posters inciting families to have only one child have been replaced by copies of regulations detailing who have the right to have a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city's government has sent family planning officials and volunteers to meet couples at their home, and to slide prospectus under their door.
He also promised to provide psychological and financial advice to those who wish to have more than one child.
According to the family planning officer, the answer was disappointing.
Disappointing response
Although those responsible in a rural city in the suburbs of Shanghai say they have seen an increase in the demand for couples wishing a second child after the campaign was launched, the more urban district reported that there was no change.
The town of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, still receives only four to five applications per month.
Shanghai officials, disappointed, say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to be only about 165,000 -- slightly higher than 2009 but less than 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee in the municipality of Caolu in Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
They want to fill their first child, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27 years old and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26 years old, said that they would love to have two children and that they are legally allowed there.
But like many Chinese, they only have the minimum health insurance and life insurance provided by the government.
Without social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
The Western people misconsider that the single child policy is a rights problem, said Yang, a construction engineer whose woman is pregnant for seven months of the couple's first child.
It's true, we're being stealing the chance of having more than one child.
But the problem is not just the law.
It's the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, Human Resources Manager, said she only wanted a single child because she was one of her own. "We were the center of the family and used to have everyone take care of us."
We are not used to taking care of someone else and we really do not want to take care of others. "
Chen Zijian, 42 years old and owner of a translation company said so more cruly.
For middle-class couples who lower birth rates, he said, we must be selfish for success.
People 20 or 30 years old grew up seeing their parents fight in the early days of capitalist China and do not want to have this lifestyle themselves, he said.
Even one child needs a lot of time from his parents, he says.
A mother must give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are space problems -- "You need to change your apartment" -- and planning -- "When your child is only 9 months old, you need to write his CV to get a place in the best kindergarten."
Most of his friends are ready for this experience once, says Chen, but not two.
"Our generation is the first to benefit from a higher standard of living," he said.
We don't want to make too much sacrifice.
