Michael Zammit Cutajar, who has written six pages of the document, has studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the Executive Secretary-General of the United Nations, Yvo de Boer, described as "the full image."
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 2020, from 25 to 45 per cent from 1990 levels, while major developing countries, over the same period, would reduce their emissions from 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union also relaunched negotiations on Friday by promising to provide $3.6 billion per year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to support floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
