The 62-year-old photographer, known for his star photos, will be tried on 15 and 16 April 2010 for abuse of weakness, a crime punishable by a maximum of three years' imprisonment and a fine of 375,000 euros.
This decision means that there will well be a trial in this case worthy of a saga on one of the richest families in France, in which mother and daughter tear up while holding the dreams of the empire of the cosmetics L'Oréal.
But the 15th Correctional Chamber also ordered that a medical expertise from Liliane Bettencourt, 87 years old, should be conducted collectively by three doctors.
The heir and principal shareholder of L'Oréal has always refused to submit to such a review, in any case not under the conditions proposed by the Nanterre Public Prosecutor's Office during the investigation.
The doctors appointed on Friday will have to report before March 10, 2010, including whether Liliane Bettencourt was in a state of weakness and at what periods.
I think she'll do it.
I'll talk to her about it, said at the end of the hearing the lawyer of Ms. Bettencourt, Mr. Georges Kiejman.
For his part, counsel for Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers, Olivier Metzner, welcomed the court's decision.
This is an excellent news (...) The expertise will demonstrate that he (Mr. Banier) manipulated this old lady that we must protect, he said.
For two years, the only daughter of Liliane Bettencourt has been in criminal proceedings against François-Marie Banier, a touch-to-all photographer and artist, who she accuses of having profited for years of her mother's weakness to get a billion euros of donations, in the form of cheques, life insurance contracts or master paintings.
For her part, Liliane Bettencourt has always refuted having been manipulated by the photographer, who she considers a long-standing friend.
While the court was to consider the admissibility of Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers's action, counsel 'pleadings sometimes turned to the great family release on Friday.
For example, Liliane Bettencourt's lawyer reported three letters sent by her client (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) to her notary, in which she said she was wary of Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers's husband.
In the 2003 mail, Liliane Bettencourt added, according to the lawyer: "Could you explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier once, twice a day for fifteen years.
Françoise, I've never been able to talk to her since her marriage. "
For her part, the Nanterre Public Prosecutor's Office again held that the complainant was not admissible to act, especially since a judge of the tutels has in recent days refused to grant her application to initiate judicial protection proceedings for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "has full capacity to act in court, she is not under protection and has no guardian.
No one else has to act in his place, "said the representative of the Public Prosecutor's Office, Marie-Chrsitine Daubigney.
The court finally decided that it would decide once the trial had taken place on the admissibility of Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers.
Management revolution or end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of the large French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence will have been vain...
For more than ten years, the attitude of the management of large companies vis-à-vis its employees, points out the position of companies vis-à-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: it is to have collaborators accede to "values" determined from above as it was before, to impose on consumers products thought by plant technicians.
By putting the client at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put market conquest strategies back there... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from customer preferences factors comes back regularly!
Demobilization of employees may lead to mortiferous demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects the managers in particular.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all intellectual functions of the company, including R & D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
The EI "requires a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision from all stakeholders"; it requires a commitment from employees that authoritarian management revenues completely contrarize.
This is why we call for a management revolution that would be to put the employees at the centre of the company's concerns as the client.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion investigations
Will internal opinion surveys - such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to his employees - encourage this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First because I could see that, in the face of a new situation, any structure finally happens, after many detours, to do priority... what she has always done.!
- Then, because authoritarianism - one of the pathologies of the lung - grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic vision of human behaviour.
Issus of the major engineering schools, they have a mechanical interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the old behavioural theory, recently reactivated by the United States' neurosciences, and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of study and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "leviers" (sic) of the commitment of the executives, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr supports the leaders in a position of mechanical governance, inappropriate to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the management revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises, requires a finalist vision of human behaviour.
It consists of integrating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental finding: for employees, commitment for the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means of realizing part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Currently, only the studies from the Motifunctional Analysis adopt this design of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their business on the basis of a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to assess what it offers them to achieve their life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and "place" their human resources management. "
They thus create a ground for the concerted development of robust and effective economic intelligence.
