Turkish justice dissolves pro-Kurdish party, a heavy decision of consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court held on Friday the dissolution of the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that was immediately followed by manifestations of anger in the Kurdish community, in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision may greatly complicate the Government's task, which has just given hands to the Kurdish community in an attempt to end 25 years of conflict.
The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved as it had become a "home of activities detrimental to the independence of the State and its indivisible unity," said the President of the Court Hasim Kiliç, after four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously by the 11 judges, while a qualified majority of seven votes was required to pronounce the dissolution, Mr. Kiliç said, adding that 37 of the party's executives, including his President Ahmet Türk and Member of Parliament Aysel Tugluk, are banished from political life for a period of five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of parliamentary immunity to which Mr. Türk and Ms. Tugluk were entitled and the confiscation by the Treasury of the party's property.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
His leaders had warned before the verdict that Members would leave Parliament rather than sit as unlabelled parliamentarians.
The decision follows a procedure initiated in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP of obeying the "directives" of the Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political window for PKK rebels.
The party, however, ensures that it does not have "no organic ties" with the PKK but refuses to qualify it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The Court's verdict intervenes as the government has just given hands to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen its rights, to try to delay Kurds' support for the PKK and to end the conflict.
DTP leaders had stated that a dissolution could lead to increased tensions in the anatolien southeast, where many protests against the conditions of detention of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan have degenerated into clashes with the police in recent weeks.
As soon as justice was announced, a thousand demonstrators gathered in front of the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the large city of southeast, which is populated by the majority of Kurds.
Law enforcement fired tear-mogen grenades and used water guns, while protesters were throwing molotov cocktails or stones, with fronds.
A hundred people also protested in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr. Türk stated that the decision of the Justice would "deepen despair."
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (Kurdish, ndlr) by banning a party, he said to the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are in principle opposed to the closure of the parties.
This does not solve anything, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a total torpedo of the democratic openness launched by the government, "said political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed an attack that had killed seven soldiers three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the most murderous in recent months.
