The cradle of dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled the other carnivorous dinosaurs: this bipede was about 2 metres long for 1.50m high, its later members were powerful, its elongated skull was equipped with acarized and plumbed teeth, its short arms ended with saucy claws and had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and his colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine, Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which at the time made part of the emerging land of the supercontinent, the Pangee and was towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt said that the discovery of the Tawa once again illuminates the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
He informs us about the relationship, distribution and characteristics of the parent.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt undertook searches with other paleontologists, on the Gohst Ranch site north of New Mexico
Randall Irmis from the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the search team tells that sometimes they found a dozen bones in one day, which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating back to the Trias.
Scientists quickly realized that part of these bones belonged to a new species.
The searches have updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories about the beginning of the evolution of dinosaurs.
The researchers baptized him as Tawa according to the word of the Hopi Indians for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare and are limited to some incomplete bone fragments.
Not all paleontology experts share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery particularly spectacular, but it makes it possible to confirm certain theories about the beginning of the evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the first dinosaurs.
The experts wonder, among other things, what time the Saurians divided into three major groups of evolution: the theropods (carnivores) that include tyrannosaure and the later-appeared velociraptor, from which the birds, the sauropods, quadrupheds in the long neck, and those related to them and the ornithisdog herbivores are part of such species as triceratops and stegosaure.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa is one of the first theropods.
This species has an interesting report of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
Researchers found clues that suggest that the Tawa hallae had small air bags in its bones at the skull level, as well as the birds that are the descendants of the theropods.
These small air pockets facilitate the breathing of birds compared to mammals.
It appears that in Tawa hallae, vertebrae was also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air bags in its bones.
As the related line of the huge sauropodes also had aerial bags and a light ossature, one can think that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive known dinosaurs lived in South America, the researchers concluded that the Sauriens had appeared there.
As a result, the three major lines of evolution divided from South America to the rest of the world, that is, all the emerging land that formed the Pangee supercontinent.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the paleontologists team also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor that would have migrated, advance the researchers.
Alan Turner of the Natural History Museum in New York and co-author of Science Studies magazine said there were at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, paleontologist in Bonn said there is an even older species, silesaure, who lived in current Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give an erroneous view because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved while there are virtually none on other continents.
On the other hand, how did dinosaurs become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary age while they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptiles branch, remains today a mystery.
At the time of the Trias, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of the current crocodiles and many other Saurians.
Towards the end of the Trias the dinosaurs spread throughout the planet thus promoting the development of many new species while others, who were related to them, disappeared between the Trias and the Jurassic.
Such a success is, however, not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two assumptions.
There may have been a massive extinction that dinosaur survived randomly while other reptiles would have disappeared.
Or then, the dinosaurs were better suited, so they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
