The S21 project: a brake for Stuttgart
The scale of the Stuttgart 21 project cannot be placed high enough.
For his supporters it is nothing less than "new heart of Europe."
S21 is much more than the landfill of a railway station, more than a colossal construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Bade-Wurtemberg, in a desperate chaos of works for about ten years.
Stuttgart 21 was born from the spirit of the 1980s.
The head-line stations, with lanes that ended in the middle of the city, had the reputation at the time to be the relics of the 19th century transport technique that had the effect of sabot brake of modern rail traffic because it was once necessary a lot of time to move locomotives from the back to the front.
Arrival, short stop, departure - that's what you have to do.
This is why head-of-line stations must disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And also in Stuttgart: a train crossing station, which is about half-way on the TransEuropean Railway Magistral between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava, hence the slogan "heart of Europe."
The implementation of the S21 project will really begin, although the visions of the 1980s have not been compatible with reality for a long time.
Even the most ambitious planners have recognized that the cost, to bury the station in the respective capitals of Hesse and Bavaria, was exorbitant.
In fact, head-of-line stations no longer pose real problems of entry and exit since there are modern trains, reversible with autorails and pilot car at both ends.
However, Stuttgart 21 is now being realised next to the new route of the inter-city line towards Ulm.
Regional and communal policies have wrecked it.
The railway company is on the side because it is the taxpayer who charges the risk of the largest infrastructure project in the Federal Republic rather than the public enterprise.
From an urban point of view, this project is relatively well justified.
We get an urban space that - if we believe the charts of the computer-generated planners - will be very verdoyant.
For the rail transport system the S21 is harmful.
The crossing station and the expansion of the section are designed for a traffic of people to which we attributed - and this is typical of the 1980s - a huge growth.
At the time there was not yet competition from cheap flights.
