75% of working mothers have had professional problems because of their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of young generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Women's Feminity and Career in Spain," carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey, carried out on 9,737 women aged 15-75 years, does not leave any room for doubt: 75% of working mothers have seen their professional career limited due to maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences in the beginning of life in a couple and the number of children, whether or not women work and the type of employment employed.
Those who do not have activity outside the home, work part-time or have a low-stable job, start up in a couple earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier, and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are pushing back entry into life as a couple and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between 35 and 49 years of age with fixed work have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after settling together. This figure is rising to 4.1 among those working in the public sector. "These data show that women with stable employment needed more time in their lives to get it, which led them to repulse the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised has a broad influence on maternity, but less on the date of common start of life, "CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado explains.
The level of education is another factor that widens the gap in the age of marriage between women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, those who have completed elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years of age on average.
"Another distinction also appears between women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have done elementary education are getting married and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have done middle or higher level studies reverse this program and give priority to obtaining stable work as a precondition for marriage and upon arrival of a child, "said Delgado.
