As has been done with the ABS brake anti-lock system and as will be done with ESP stability control, emergency braking aid systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory for new registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a period of deficiency has been fixed until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure, imposed by the European Union, is to strengthen pedestrian protection, although by its way of action it can also help to avoid many back shocks.
The emergency braking assistant shall act by increasing the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency detected by the system through the driver's shot.
But the latter does not always maintain pressure until the end.
According to a study by the Bosch car component manufacturer, one third of the drivers involved in an accident could not press the brake before the collision, and half of them did not benefit from its full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, in turn, requires the maximum brake system, reducing the distance that the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with this type of component, up to 1,100 fatal accidents in which pedestrians are involved could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even more important with the popularization of the so-called smart emergency braking systems: it is calculated that one in four sinks with injuries would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, through radar or camera, detects obstacles and prevents the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps him by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device exercises the maximum effort on the brakes in order to minimize damage.
